          "body": "Verse 8 jolts the chapter from messianic radiance to judgment oracle without transition. *The Lord sends a message against Jacob, and it falls on Israel.* The chapter's second half (9:8-21) is the first three stanzas of a four-part judgment poem (concluded at 10:1-4), each stanza closing with the same dreadful refrain: *In spite of all this, His anger does not turn away and His hand is still stretched out* (9:12, 17, 21). The first stanza diagnoses Israel's heart: *bricks have fallen down, but we will rebuild with smooth stones; sycamores have been cut down, but we will replace them with cedars* (9:10). Discipline is read as construction setback to be upgraded — the chastening of God absorbed as an opportunity for self-improvement. This is the most chilling response to divine discipline in Scripture: not denial, not even despair, but *defiant renovation*."
