          "title": "The refrain that refuses closure",
          "body": "Three times in this chapter (and once more at 10:4), the same nine Hebrew words close each judgment stanza: *be-khol-zot lo-shav appo ve-od yado netuyah*. The refrain is the chapter's heartbeat. After Aram and Philistia devour Israel from both sides (9:12) — still stretched out. After the elder and the lying prophet are cut off in a single day (9:14-17) — still stretched out. After wickedness burns like a forest fire and brothers consume brothers (9:18-21) — still stretched out. The chapter's pastoral payoff is in verse 13: *Yet the people do not turn back to Him who struck them, nor do they seek the LORD of hosts*. The wrath continues because the repentance never comes. Every stroke was meant to be the last — meant to drive the people back. The hand remains stretched out not because God refuses to relent but because the people refuse to turn."
